SIMPLE: thing
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Thing
<hw>Thing</hw> <pr>(th⟦icr⟧ng)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS.
<ets>⟦thorn⟧ing</ets> a thing, cause, assembly, judicial assembly; akin
to <ets>⟦thorn⟧ingan</ets> to negotiate, <ets>⟦thorn⟧ingian</ets> to
reconcile, conciliate, D. <ets>ding</ets> a thing, OS. <ets>thing</ets>
thing, assembly, judicial assembly, G. <ets>ding</ets> a thing, formerly
also, an assembly, court, Icel. <ets>⟦thorn⟧ing</ets> a thing, assembly,
court, Sw. & Dan. <ets>ting</ets>; perhaps originally used of the
transaction of or before a popular assembly, or the time appointed for
such an assembly; cf. G. <ets>dingen</ets> to bargain, hire, MHG.
<ets>dingen</ets> to hold court, speak before a court, negotiate, Goth.
<ets>⟦thorn⟧eihs</ets> time, perhaps akin to L. <ets>tempus</ets> time.
Cf. <er>Hustings</er>, and <er>Temporal</er> of time.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Whatever exists, or is conceived to exist, as a separate entity,
whether animate or inanimate; any separable or distinguishable object of
thought.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>God made . . . every <qex>thing</qex> that creepeth upon the earth
after his kind.</q> <rj><qau>Gen. i. 25.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He sent after this manner; ten asses laden with the good
<qex>things</qex> of Egypt.</q> <rj><qau>Gen. xiv. 23.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A <qex>thing</qex> of beauty is a joy forever.</q>
<rj><qau>Keats.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An inanimate object, in distinction from a living
being; any lifeless material.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Ye meads and groves, unconscious <qex>things</qex>!</q>
<rj><qau>Cowper.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A transaction or occurrence; an event; a
deed.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>[And Jacob said] All these <qex>things</qex> are against me.</q>
<rj><qau>Gen. xlii. 36.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Which if ye tell me, I in like wise will tell you by what
authority I do these <qex>things</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Matt. xxi.
24.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A portion or part; something.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Wicked men who understand any <qex>thing</qex> of wisdom.</q>
<rj><qau>Tillotson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>A diminutive or slighted object; any object viewed
as merely existing; -- often used in pity or contempt.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>See, sons, what <qex>things</qex> you are!</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The poor <qex>thing</qex> sighed, and . . . turned from me.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I'll be this abject <qex>thing</qex> no more.</q>
<rj><qau>Granville.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I have a <qex>thing</qex> in prose.</q>
<rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <pluf>pl.</pluf> <def>Clothes; furniture; appurtenances;
luggage; <as>as, to pack or store one's <ex>things</ex></as>.</def>
<mark>[Colloq.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ Formerly, the singular was sometimes used in a plural or
collective sense.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And them she gave her moebles and her <qex>thing</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Thing</xex> was used in a very general sense in Old
English, and is still heard colloquially where some more definite term
would be used in careful composition.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In the garden [he] walketh to and fro,⟦br⟧
And hath his <qex>things</qex> [<it>i. e.</it>, prayers, devotions] said
full courteously.</q> <rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Hearkening his minstrels their <qex>things</qex> play.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>Whatever may be possessed or owned;
a property; -- distinguished from <xex>person</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <pr>[<it>In this sense pronounced</it> t⟦icr⟧ng.]</pr>
<def>In Scandinavian countries, a legislative or judicial
assembly.</def> <rj><au>Longfellow.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Things personal</b></col>. <fld>(Law)</fld> <cd>Same as
<cref>Personal property</cref>, under <er>Personal</er>.</cd> --
<col><b>Things real</b></col>. <cd>Same as <cref>Real property</cref>,
under <er>Real</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ting</ent>⟦br⟧
<ent>Thing</ent>⟦br⟧
